          "body": "Verses 59-63 are the chapter's most theologically charged passage and they are routinely underread. Three lay families (652 persons, v. 60) and three priestly families (vv. 61-62) could not produce documentation of their Israelite descent. The lay families are registered but presumably absorbed into the community at a lower standing — their ambiguity is noted but does not generate a judicial ruling. The priestly families, however, face a harder verdict: 'they were considered unclean and excluded from the priesthood' (v. 62). The distinction is precise: lay identity can be imprecise and still permit participation in the assembly; priestly identity demands verification because access to the most holy things carries a death-penalty liability (Leviticus 22:10-16; Numbers 18:7). The governor's response is theologically exemplary: he does not expel them permanently, nor does he admit them on good faith. He defers: 'until a priest stood up with Urim and Thummim' (v. 63). Human record-keeping has reached its limit; divine adjudication must decide. The passage is a model of institutional humility — the community holds the question open, applies the standard as far as it can reach, and then waits on God."
